4 A BILL FOR AN ACT ENTITLED: “AN ACT ESTABLISHING THE JIM LOUD THUNDER GOPHER MEMORIAL
5 HIGHWAY IN CASCADE COUNTY; DIRECTING THE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION TO INSTALL
6 SIGNS AND TO INCLUDE THE MEMORIAL HIGHWAY ON THE NEXT PUBLICATION OF THE STATE MAP;
7 AND PROVIDING AN IMMEDIATE EFFECTIVE DATE.”
8
9 WHEREAS, Jim Loud Thunder Gopher was born in 1885 in Malta, Montana, a full-blood Ojibwe of the
10 Crane Clan; and
11 WHEREAS, after a period of searching and hardship following the Spanish Flu pandemic, Loud
12 Thunder Gopher moved to Hill 57 outside of Great Falls; and
13 WHEREAS, the Little Shell Tribe had historic homesites on Hill 57 just below Mount Royal. The area is
14 within the tribe's congressionally designated service area pursuant to the Little Shell Restoration Act of 2019;
15 and
16 WHEREAS, Loud Thunder Gopher was a spiritual practitioner of Ojibwe traditional teachings, and he
17 organized ceremonial practices, including the Sun Dance, Midewiwin, shaking tent, sweat lodge, Round Dance,
18 and Give Away ceremonies. As a community organizer, Loud Thunder Gopher promoted voter registration and
19 agricultural employment; and
20 WHEREAS, in 1942 Loud Thunder Gopher was selected as a member of the Landless Indians to travel
21 to Washington, D.C., with Raymond Gray and Packy Myers to advocate for a land base; and
22 WHEREAS, Loud Thunder Gopher died in 1946 in Great Falls and is buried in Highland Cemetery. His
23 descendants are enrolled in many of the tribes residing in Montana.
24
25 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF MONTANA:
26
27 NEW SECTION. Section 1. Jim Loud Thunder Gopher memorial highway. (1) There is
28 established the Jim Loud Thunder Gopher memorial highway on the existing northwest bypass and Vaughn
